node.title: In Surprising Move, Canada Rules Boeing Out of Finalists to Build New Fighter Planes
node.description: The finalists, Lockheed Martin's F-35 stealth fighter and Saab's Gripen, surprised many as American aerospace giant Boeing's Super Hornet was left out.

node.title: If you think this is rats jumping off a sinking political ship, think again
node.description: The departure of some of the nation's most high-profile Liberal politicians on the eve on an election easily lends itself to the suggestion of rats fleeing a sinking ship. But as the last poll showed, it's not over until the votes are cast, writes political correspondent Brett Worthington.

node.title: Jacuzzi acquires NZ spa pool company Vortex
node.description: The Nelson-based company, the world's largest dedicated spa retailer, been acquired by US brand Jacuzzi.

node.title: Widow of man paralysed on 69th birthday says NDIS threshold has 'got to be fixed'
node.description: Both major parties have been accused of "shameful" inaction over the NDIS age cut-off. Now, advocates are fighting to make it a federal election issue.

node.title: Thunderstorm asthma warning for Melbourne and surrounds as more storms to lash the city
node.description: Melburnians are once again being told to batten down the hatches while remaining on high alert for thunderstorm asthma conditions, with forecast high pollen levels and strong winds sparking warnings.

node.title: PM accuses Labor of 'disgraceful slur' over Home Affairs contracts awarded to two close friends
node.description: Scott Morrison hits back at any suggestion he had a role in the Home Affairs Department awarding an almost $80,000 contract to a company run by two of his closest friends.

node.title: Too early to say potential size of Nelson Covid-19 outbreak - Chief Medical Officer
node.description: Nelson-Marlborough District Health Board's Chief Medical Officer says it's too early to say how large the latest Covid-19 outbreak in the region will end up.

node.title: The Clock Is Ticking as Baseball Veers Toward a Lockout
node.description: With the collective bargaining agreement set to expire this week, owners and players are negotiating over the sport’s future. A work stoppage seems inevitable.

node.title: Citing Covid-19, Climate and Wars, U.N. Asks Donors for Big Jump in Funding
node.description: The world body said it needed $41 billion to fund humanitarian aid to help 183 million people in 63 countries.

node.title: Colorado Panel Says Erratic Behavior Not a Reason to Use Ketamine as Restraint
node.description: The panel was announced last year, saying it would review the state's ketamine waiver, which allows workers to use the drug outsides of hospitals.

node.title: This Platform Stripped 'Jeopardy!' Champ Matt Amodio of His Checkmark: What is Twitter?
node.description: "I never thought trying to fight cancer would be what gets me canceled," Amodio tweeted.

node.title: Man accused of helping to kidnap Stuart MacGill was a bikie on parole, court told
node.description: A man accused of involvement in the alleged kidnapping of former cricketer Stuart MacGill was on parole at the time and is allegedly an affiliate of the Comanchero motorcycle gang, a Sydney court has heard.

node.title: Big bank mortgages below 2 per cent going, going, gone
node.description: Mortgages from the big four banks with a '1' in front of the interest rate are now a thing of the past, while investors take over as the drivers of lending and property price growth.

node.title: Planned Parenthood Says Hacker Compromised Information for 400,000 Patients
node.description: The group’s Los Angeles affiliate said it did not know who was responsible for the ransomware attack and did not believe any information had been used for “fraudulent purposes.”

node.title: People will need to be fully vaccinated to book DOC huts and campsites
node.description: Visitors will need to confirm all of their party is fully vaccinated when booking.

node.title: Companies Tell Feds Supply Chain Bottlenecks, Worker Retention Rate Among Inflation Issues
node.description: Businesses heard a plethora of reasons for the staff shortage, including no childcare, retirements, and concerns regarding COVID, according to the Fed report.

node.title: The $35 hardware in your home that could cost you $14,000
node.description: There's a hidden flood risk in your home and it has absolutely nothing to do with the rain, or your drains. But it could cost you tens of thousands of dollars if you don't sort it out.

node.title: Greg Hunt confirms he's retiring from politics at the next election
node.description: Federal Health and Aged Care Minister Greg Hunt announces he will retire at the next election and not recontest his seat in Victoria.

node.title: Saluting Hanukkah, Biden Says Menorah Shows 'There Is Still Light' to Overcome Darkness
node.description: The president added that the light could "illuminate a path forward."

node.title: Mum threatened at knifepoint with children in car
node.description: Police allege the woman parked her Range Rover station wagon at her Klemzig home around 3:20pm yesterday and was approached by a man armed with a knife.

node.title: Scores of protesters demand a drink at 'freedom pub' after anti-vax licensee convicted
node.description: Demonstrators waved placards decrying "tyranny" and called for "justice" outside Singleton Court. Inside, Bradley John Hill's matter was dealt with in five minutes.

node.title: Victorian government's pandemic bill passes upper house
node.description: After weeks of negotiations and substantial amendments, the Victorian government's controversial pandemic legislation has cleared its last hurdle.

node.title: Covid-19: 172 new community cases reported in New Zealand today
node.description: There are 172 new community cases of Covid-19 in New Zealand today, with new cases in Northland, Auckland, Waikato, Bay of Plenty, Lakes and the Nelson/Tasman region.

node.title: Bridges named as National's finance and infrastructure spokesperson
node.description: National's new leader Chris Luxon has given Simon Bridges the Finance and Infrastructure portfolios, although Bridges was unable to make it to the announcement.

node.title: Bill Clinton Pays Tribute to Jacqueline Avant, Wife of Music Legend Killed in Robbery
node.description: "She inspired admiration, respect & affection in everyone who knew her. We are heartbroken. She will be deeply missed," the former president said on Twitter.

node.title: Man Charged With Killing Couple, Burning Their Residences in Heroin Money Dispute Arraigned
node.description: A man pleaded not guilty in a Vermont court Wednesday to two counts of aggravated murder related to a 2018 shooting allegedly over $20,000 in drug money.

node.title: Anti-vaccination Christian broadcaster dies after contracting COVID-19
node.description: Founder of American religious network Daystar TV, Marcus Lamb, dies weeks after contracting COVID-19, as a review into claims of disinformation finds no breach of Australian TV codes.

node.title: 4 takeaways from the third day of the Ghislaine Maxwell trial.
node.description: The defense cross-examined a woman identified only as “Jane” for hours, attempting to poke holes in her story of abuse.

node.title: Biden Says U.S. Needs to Confront Inequity in Medicine to Help End HIV/AIDS Epidemic
node.description: Biden acknowledged that LGBT and racial minority groups have "endured the brunt" of an epidemic that's killed 700,000 Americans and 36 million globally.

node.title: 'On the right side of history': tennis great Billie Jean King backs WTA stand over Peng Shuai
node.description: The tennis world responds to the WTA suspending tournaments in China due to concerns over the treatment of Peng Shuai, with the organisation receiving support from the likes of Billie Jean King, Martina Navratilova and Andy Roddick.
